data.content:
Here are the modern MSTest replacements for each assertion:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed:**

| Before (`Assert.IsTrue`) | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Clearer intent, better failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Shows expected vs actual count on failure |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | Asserts exactly one match and returns it |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` | *(kept as-is)* | No built-in "all match predicate" assertion in MSTest |

The `All(u => u.IsActive)` check is the one case where `Assert.IsTrue` is still appropriate — MSTest doesn't have a dedicated "all items match predicate" assertion. These require **MSTest 3.8+**.
